        <h3 style="text-align: center;">About Codebie</h3>
       <p>
        An online judge is an automatic system to test problems and give verdicts. An online judge can compile, execute your code, and match your output with the correct output. 
        <br><br>The main objective of this website is to make a platform for Aust Students to practice their CSE courses offline/online lab tasks. So many students face problems to find out whether their code is correct or not. There is a possibility your code can fail for large inputs or corner cases. But online judge tests your code with so many cases with large input and corner case. So if your code passes in an online judge it is guaranteed your code is correct.
        <br><br>There are six sections in Codebie. They are C, C++, Java, Python, Data Structure, Algorithm. Questions and Tutorials are separated for each section. In each section, questions are sorted according to their difficulty.
        <br><br>A problem contains the following parts,
        <br>Statement: Describing the problem
        <br>Input Format: The way inputs will be given
        <br>Constraints: Limit of inputs
        <br>Output Format: The way you need to print the output 
        <br>Then you will be given some sample input, output to check this locally before submitting the code. Every question will contain at least one hidden input which will not be shown but will be testing while judging the code. So your code needs to pass every input, output to get an 'Accepted' verdict.
        
        <br><br>There are five verdicts as following,
        <br>Accepted: Your code passed all cases.
        <br>Wrong Answer: There is at least one case where your code gives a wrong output.
        <br>Time Limit Exceeded: There is at least one case where your code fails to run within a given time limit.
        <br>Runtime Error: There is at least one case where your code gives an exception
        <br>Compilation Error: Your code fails to compile.
        <br><br>To avoid plagiarism, you can only see other's submissions of a specific problem only if you have 'Accepted' verdict on that problem. You can see in the rank list to compare yourself with other users. The recent tab will show the last 30 submissions of all users.
        <br><br>On the profile page, you can edit your name and change your password and see your statistics. Also, you can view other's profiles.
       </p>
